===Verb===
{{en-verb|holds out|holding out|held out}}

# {{&lit|hold|out|lang=en}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[hold]] (something) [[out]]; to [[extend]] (something) forward.
#* '''1883''', {{w|Robert Louis Stevenson}}, ''{{w|Treasure Island}}''
#*: I '''held out''' my hand, and the horrible, soft-spoken, eyeless creature gripped it in a moment like a vise. I was so much startled that I struggled to withdraw; but the blind man pulled me close up to him with a single action of his arm.
# {{lb|en|idiomatic|often|with ''for''}} To [[wait]], or [[refuse]] in hopes of getting something better (from a negotiation, etc.)
#: ''I am '''holding out''' for more money.''
#: ''How long has he been '''holding out'''?''
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} To survive, [[endure]].
#: ''How long can they '''hold out''' without water?''
#* {{quote-journal
|date=September 2, 2011
|author=
|title=Wales 2-1 Montenegro
|work=BBC
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/14660870.stm
|page=
|passage=Stevan Jovetic gave Montenegro hope when he unleashed a pile-driver but Wales '''held out''' for a much-needed win.}}
# {{lb|en|idiomatic|usually|with ''on''}} To withhold something.
#: ''You've got a key! Why have you been '''holding out''' on me?''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To set something aside or save it for later.
#: ''Pack the boxes, but '''hold out''' a few blue ones for later.''

